Reflection-action run for 2026-07-11 (executed 2026-07-12, unattended).
Baseline before touching anything: working tree clean, tsc clean, 118/118 tests passing.
After: 142/142 tests passing (24 new), typecheck clean, 3 commits pushed to origin/main.

ITEM 1 — "Check email.send credentials/config — 0s failure means it never reached the provider."
Credentials are fine: verified the Mailjet API key/secret from .env against
api.mailjet.com (read-only /v3/REST/sender call → HTTP 200). The failure was
not config. Job 6b8b5adf ("summarize recent commits across my repos and email
me") failed email.send at 9ms with: invalid 'to' address "$step_2.user.email".
Chain: the task said "email me" → the planner called users.lookup with a
self-referential query → nothing in the directory is literally named "me" →
lookupUser returned null → $step_2.user.email couldn't resolve → the literal
placeholder string reached email.send as the recipient. Note this run
(06:52 UTC) predates the unresolved-reference gate committed in 453a14d
(09:47 UTC same day), which now fails such steps with a diagnosis. FIXED the
root cause a layer deeper: lookupUser now resolves self-referential queries
(me / myself / my email / the operator / owner / the requester / current
user…) to the operator — the oldest superadmin — and users.lookup's
description tells the planner so. New regression tests cover the query
classifier. Commit f9af254.

ITEM 2 — "Retry github.list_repos manually — auth, rate limit, or transient? read_repo worked, token likely has partial scope."
Retried manually: the GITHUB_TOKEN currently in .env returns 200 on both
/user and /user/repos — the exact call list_repos makes. The failure was
auth ("Bad credentials", 401): the token was invalid at 06:52 UTC and the
operator rotated it at 10:53 (+0200) the same morning (.env mtime), so
nothing more to fix on the config side. The "partial scope" inference was
wrong though, and pointed at a real code bug: all github.* calls share one
Octokit client and one token — read_repo only "worked" because its four
helpers (readme/recentCommits/openPRs/openIssues) catch ALL errors and
return empty, so on the dead token it returned {readme:null, commits:[],
prs:[], issues:[]} as a fake success and the job summarized commits from no
data. FIXED: those helpers now rethrow 401 with the actual cause; 404-shaped
cases (missing README, empty repo) still degrade to empty as intended.
Commit f8454b5.

ITEM 3 — "Improve skill picker matching: both picks scored 15 (keyword-only) — add better descriptions or embeddings."
CONFIRMED-NOT-A-BUG, no change made. Score 15 means the keyword leg fired
without intent corroboration, but both picks were correct, not coin flips:
email-writing matched a task that literally asked to email a summary
(intent was "summarize" — the primary deliverable — so the draft-email
intent leg correctly didn't fire; the keyword leg exists precisely for this
secondary-action case), and both tasks succeeded with quality.check passing.
The suggested remedies also don't fit: skill descriptions are never scored
(they only feed the planner's catalog listing), so "better descriptions"
would change nothing, and switching to embeddings is an architecture
decision the operator should make deliberately — two successful picks are
no evidence for it. The keyword patterns are curated routing rules with
regression guards (see the 2026-07-08/09 pattern-tightening history in
skills.ts), which is the opposite of guessing.

ITEM 4 — "If research latency matters, consider caching or scoping research.deep — 124s per call, every call."
The premise was doubled: the "2 runs, 248s" were ONE 124s call recorded
twice — a delegated task persists two job records (the delegating job
mirrors the peer's runs back; the peer writes its own peer:delegate record)
and reflection's aggregate() counted both (jobs b8678f0d/d6dd5900 carry
byte-identical runs arrays). FIXED the double-count: aggregate() now skips
run aggregation for mirror records (result.peer set), counting runs where
they executed. Commit 5c134ef. On the call itself: that task ("summarize
recent commits…") should never have used research.deep — that misroute was
already fixed in 1aa0b74, which landed 42 minutes AFTER this run, so it
can't recur. research.deep already has a depth cap (NEUROWORKS_RESEARCH_MAX_DEPTH,
default 3), parallel vault+web search, per-URL fetch cache, and a 512-token
synth cap from earlier optimization passes. Query-level result caching is a
staleness-vs-latency trade-off left to the operator; not taken unilaterally.

NOT DONE / FOR THE OPERATOR
- Nothing outstanding from this reflection's items. One observation worth
